Bayesian Analysis in R using High Level Stan Libraries

BioData Club

Jose Laborde PhD

10/16/2020

An elevator summary of Bayesian Analysis

  • More than one way to do a statistical analysis.
  • Usually the parameters to be estimated are considered fixed but unknown numbers (like the betas in regression)
  • In the usual “frequentist” way, these betas are then estimated and those estimations are tested with some significance level (p-values and all).
  • Although there are interval estimations the estimators themselves along with the inference performed on them have to have a weird assumption of “if we could repeat this sampling process 100 times, we would see that 5% of time the estimation would differ from the hypothesis”
  • In Bayesian analysis the parameters are not considered fixed numbers. Instead these are considered random variables and so the end result of the analysis is an estimation of the entire distribution of the parameters of interest.
  • Once we have a distribution at hand, one can compute any statistic we want from it e.g. histograms, intervals, medians, modes, quantiles, etc.
  • The inference that comes along a Bayesian analysis is therefore intuitive and does not have to assume anything about samples we never took.

The tricky but fun part: Bayes Theorem

\[p(\theta|D) = \frac{p(D|\theta)p(\theta)}{p(D)}\] where:

  • \(\theta\): parameter(s) of the model.
  • \(D\): is the data (usually \(X_1, X_2, \dots, X_n\))
  • \(p(\theta|D)\): posterior distribution of the parameter(s)
  • \(p(D|\theta)\): Likelihood function (Yes, the same one as in the frequentist analysis)
  • \(p(\theta)\): prior distribution of the parameter(s) (Here we store any previous knowledge of the parameters)
  • \(p(D)\): normalizing constant (the integral of the numerator is the marginal distribution of \(D\)).

What we will learn:

  • Use RStanArm’s functionality to model a multiple regression using stan_glm.
  • Use bayestestR to look at the inference results.
  • Use bayesplot to visualize the estimation’s results.

What we won’t discuss:

  • Prior distributions in depth. We will stick to default priors (weakly informative priors based on their scale). Keep in mind that these are usually the best choices when we lack historic information on parameters.
  • How to build a model from first principles using Stan only. This type of modeling is required when we wish to do a non standard statistical analysis or a custom inference for very specific reasons. Most of the time, if we need to to LMs, GLMs, and so forth, we should be good with RStanArm.
  • We won’t go in depth with model diagnostics here. That is an extensive topic on its own.

The usual frequentist model:

For the multiple linear regression model \[y = \alpha + \beta_1x_1 + \dots + \beta_kx_k + \epsilon\] we typically assume a Gaussian Likelihood and fixed unknown parameters: \[y \sim N(\mu, \sigma^2)\] with \(\mu = \alpha + \beta_1x_1 + \dots + \beta_kx_k\), \(\epsilon \sim N(0,\sigma^2)\), \(\beta_1, \dots \beta_k\) fixed but unknown. The statistical problem is then to estimate the value of the \(\beta_i\)s. This is usually done via maximum likelihood and R has the lm function just for that.

data("mtcars")
head(mtcars)
mpgFormula = as.formula(mpg ~ cyl 
                            + hp 
                            + drat 
                            + wt 
                            + qsec 
                            + gear 
                            + carb)
freqModel = lm(mpgFormula, data = mtcars)
summary(freqModel)

We see from this model the only “significant” parameter is \(\hat{\beta}_{wt}\) (assuming a significance level of 5%). From the usual hypothesis testing procedure we would need to say that "if we took 100 different samples, 95 of those would show us that \(\beta_{wt}\)s estimate should show a p-value smaller than the significance level (or a the confidence interval would not contain zero 95 out of 100 times). We are all used to that concept. However why are we making a conclusion based on samples we never took? This is weird.

We are all very used the convenience and ease of use of the lm function and other similar ones (glm, lmer, etc.) which have similar syntax by having a formula and a dataset as the 2 main parameters and maybe also a link function (in the case of glm with a gaussian link this is exactly the same as an lm).

The bayesian model:

In the bayesian framework we also have a likelihood function linking the model parameters with the data, however here the model parameters themselves are not fixed constants but random variables instead. The estimation problem becomes one of an entire distribution rather than a point. We have: \[y \sim N(\alpha + \beta_1x_1 + \dots + \beta_kx_k, \sigma^2)\] with \[\alpha \sim \pi_\alpha\] \[\beta_i \sim \pi_i, i=1, 2, \dots, k\] \[\sigma \sim \pi_\sigma\] where \(\pi\)s are prior distributions for each parameter to be estimated.

  • Note: If we were to do this estimation using RStan alone, we would need to specify the priors above. Since we are using RStanarm this package takes care of this for us whenever we do not provide any priors.
library(rstanarm) # stan_glm

## This is rstanarm version 2.21.1

## - For execution on a local, multicore CPU with excess RAM we recommend calling
##   options(mc.cores = parallel::detectCores())

Look at the tests for this model

So how about some sort of Hypothesis testing? Let’s use bayestestR for that.

library(bayestestR) # describe_posterior
bayesModel_posterior = as.matrix(bayesModel)
bayesModel_Test = describe_posterior(bayesModel)
# This will make the rownames as the first column in the data frame
rownames(bayesModel_Test) = bayesModel_Test[,1]
# This will remove the first column since the rownames are already stored
bayesModel_Test = bayesModel_Test[,-1]
bayesModel_Test = round(bayesModel_Test,3)
kable(bayesModel_Test, 'html', booktabs = TRUE, linesep = '', caption = 'Tests for Bayesian Regression Model Results for MPG')%>%
  kable_styling(font_size = 15.0)%>%
  footnote(number = c('ROPE = region of practical equivalence'))

1 ROPE = region of practical equivalence
  • So what is the ROPE? check this: https://easystats.github.io/bayestestR/articles/region_of_practical_equivalence.html
  • In essence, it is a null region (an interval around zero) tested against the parameter’s estimated distribution. If they overlap more than just a little bit, then you accept the Null. Yes. Accept.
  • For linear models (lm), the ROPE is: \[[−0.1∗SD_y, 0.1∗SD_y]\]
  • We see that the end result is that the ROPE percentage is consistent with the frequentist conclusion with respect to the wt variable.

There are other interesting results we can show:

# Compute indices
pd = p_direction(bayesModel)
percentage_in_rope = rope(bayesModel, ci=1)
# ci: The Credible Interval (CI) probability, corresponding to the proportion of HDI, to use for the percentage in ROPE.
# HDI: Highest Density Interval

# Visualize the pd (Probability of Direction)
plot(pd)

# Visualize the percentage in ROPE
plot(percentage_in_rope)

Using the plot function

rstanarm also has it’s own overloaded plot function. It will the credible intervals:

plot(bayesModel)

Another plotting tool: bayesplot

We could use bayesplot instead to visualize the results as densities or CIs:

library(bayesplot)
## This is bayesplot version 1.7.2
## - Online documentation and vignettes at mc-stan.org/bayesplot
## - bayesplot theme set to bayesplot::theme_default()
##    * Does _not_ affect other ggplot2 plots
##    * See ?bayesplot_theme_set for details on theme setting
library(ggplot2)
color_scheme_set("purple")
plot_title = ggtitle("Posterior Intervals",
                     "with medians and 80% area")
mcmc_areas(bayesModel_posterior,
               pars = colnames(bayesModel_posterior[,4:9]),
               prob = 0.80) + plot_title

We can Also look at a basic diagnostic plot called “trace plot” which let’s us visualize the MCMC chains.

x = as.array(bayesModel, pars = colnames(bayesModel_posterior))
mcmc_trace(x, facet_args = list(nrow = 5)) + ggplot2::scale_color_discrete()
